  <!-- ========== SECTION 01: IDEs & CODE EDITORS ========== -->
  <section id="ides-code-editors" class="ess-section" aria-label="IDEs and code editors">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">01</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">IDEs & Code Editors</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Where you write code matters significantly for productivity. The right editor reduces friction, catches errors early, and makes refactoring safer. Modern editors blur the line between lightweight text editors and full IDEs. We examine the most popular choices, their strengths, and where each excels.</p>

      <!-- ===== Visual Studio Code ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="vscode">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="16 18 22 12 16 6"></polyline><polyline points="8 6 2 12 8 18"></polyline></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Visual Studio Code</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">The developer's Swiss Army knife</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Visual Studio Code has become the de facto standard for web development and is increasingly popular across all programming domains. Built by Microsoft as an Electron app, VS Code strikes an impressive balance between performance, extensibility, and ease of use. What sets it apart is the ecosystem. Over 40,000 extensions cover nearly every language, framework, and workflow imaginable.</p>
          <p>The editor itself is fast and responsive despite being built on web technologies. IntelliSense provides context-aware code completion that genuinely improves productivity. The integrated terminal, debugging tools, and Git support mean you rarely need to leave the editor. Remote development capabilities let you code on containers, WSL, or SSH targets as if they were local.</p>
          <p>VS Code's popularity means extensive community support. Nearly any problem you encounter has been solved and documented. The extension marketplace is curated well enough that finding quality tools is straightforward. Updates ship monthly with noticeable improvements.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>IntelliSense code completion with context awareness across 50+ languages</li>
              <li>Built-in Git integration with visual diff, staging, and merge conflict resolution</li>
              <li>Integrated debugging for Node.js, Python, C++, and more with breakpoints and watch expressions</li>
              <li>Extension marketplace with 40,000+ extensions covering languages, themes, and tools</li>
              <li>Remote development over SSH, containers, and WSL without performance penalty</li>
              <li>Live Share for real-time collaborative editing and debugging</li>
              <li>Multi-cursor editing and sophisticated find-and-replace with regex support</li>
              <li>Workspace settings and project-specific configurations</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Completely free and open source with no limitations</li>
                <li>Vast extension ecosystem solves nearly any workflow need</li>
                <li>Excellent performance despite Electron base</li>
                <li>Strong language support out of the box</li>
                <li>Frequent updates with meaningful improvements</li>
                <li>Remote development capabilities are game-changing</li>
                <li>Cross-platform with consistent experience</li>
                <li>Low resource usage compared to full IDEs</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Extension quality varies significantly</li>
                <li>Can feel overwhelming to configure optimally</li>
                <li>Not as powerful as JetBrains IDEs for refactoring</li>
                <li>Some Microsoft telemetry by default (can be disabled)</li>
                <li>Large projects can experience slowdown</li>
                <li>Learning curve for advanced features</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__setup">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Setup & Configuration Tips</h4>
            <ol class="ess-tool__setup-list">
              <li>Download from <code>code.visualstudio.com</code> and install for your platform</li>
              <li>Install essential extensions: ESLint/Pylint for linting, Prettier for formatting, GitLens for enhanced Git features</li>
              <li>Configure settings sync to share configurations across machines via GitHub or Microsoft account</li>
              <li>Customize keybindings early to match your workflow and muscle memory</li>
              <li>Set up language-specific extensions and debugger configurations for your primary stack</li>
              <li>Enable auto-save to reduce manual save friction during development</li>
              <li>Configure integrated terminal to use your preferred shell (bash, zsh, PowerShell)</li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>VSCodium</strong>
                <p>VS Code without Microsoft branding and telemetry. Same functionality, fully open source.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Sublime Text</strong>
                <p>Faster startup and responsiveness. Costs $99 but offers unlimited trial. Smaller extension ecosystem.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Sublime Text ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="sublime-text">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M13 2L3 14h9l-1 8 10-12h-9l1-8z"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Sublime Text</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Speed and elegance refined</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$99</span>
          <span class="tag">Unlimited Trial</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Sublime Text prioritizes performance above all else. It starts instantly, handles massive files without breaking a sweat, and responds to every keystroke without lag. Built in C++ rather than Electron, the difference is immediately noticeable. If you work with large codebases or files exceeding several megabytes, Sublime Text remains fluid where other editors struggle.</p>
          <p>The multi-cursor editing implementation is the best in class. Once you internalize the workflow, editing becomes remarkably efficient. Goto Anything lets you navigate projects by fuzzy filename, symbol, or line number with blazing speed. The minimap provides spatial awareness in long files that proves surprisingly useful.</p>
          <p>The $99 price includes all updates within a major version and works across all platforms. You can evaluate indefinitely with occasional purchase prompts. The extension ecosystem is smaller than VS Code but covers essential needs. Package Control makes installation straightforward.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>Native performance handles files of any size without performance degradation</li>
              <li>Multiple selections and split editing accelerate bulk changes</li>
              <li>Goto Anything for instant project-wide navigation</li>
              <li>Command palette for keyboard-driven workflow</li>
              <li>Distraction-free mode hides everything except code</li>
              <li>Python-based plugin API for customization</li>
              <li>Project-specific settings and build systems</li>
              <li>Instant project switching without window management</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Exceptional speed and responsiveness</li>
                <li>Handles files of any size effortlessly</li>
                <li>Multi-cursor editing is best-in-class</li>
                <li>Minimal resource usage</li>
                <li>Clean, distraction-free interface</li>
                <li>Unlimited evaluation period</li>
                <li>One-time purchase, not subscription</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Costs $99 after evaluation</li>
                <li>Smaller extension ecosystem than VS Code</li>
                <li>Less powerful for complex debugging</li>
                <li>No built-in Git UI</li>
                <li>Updates are less frequent</li>
                <li>Learning curve for advanced features</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Atom</strong>
                <p>GitHub's editor, now maintained by community. Free but slower than Sublime. Being sunset in favor of VS Code.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Vim / Neovim ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="vim-neovim">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="4 17 10 11 4 5"></polyline><line x1="12" y1="19" x2="20" y2="19"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Vim / Neovim</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Terminal-native power editing</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
          <span class="tag">Terminal</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Vim represents a fundamentally different editing philosophy. Modal editing means you switch between modes for different tasks: normal mode for navigation, insert mode for typing, visual mode for selection. The learning curve is steep. For the first weeks, you'll be slower than with any other editor. After the hump, editing speed increases dramatically.</p>
          <p>Neovim modernizes Vim's codebase with better extensibility, async support, and Lua configuration. The distinction matters for plugin authors more than users, but Neovim's momentum has made it the preferred choice for new users. LSP (Language Server Protocol) integration brings IDE features to the terminal.</p>
          <p>Why choose Vim? It's available on every Unix system. You can edit files on remote servers without installing anything. Once internalized, the keybindings become automatic. Your hands never leave the home row. Many developers use Vim keybindings in other editors via plugins, testament to the model's efficiency.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>Modal editing separates navigation from text input for efficiency</li>
              <li>Composable commands create powerful editing operations from simple primitives</li>
              <li>Runs in terminal, works over SSH without additional setup</li>
              <li>Minimal resource usage, starts instantly</li>
              <li>Extensible via Vimscript or Lua (Neovim)</li>
              <li>LSP integration provides IDE features in terminal</li>
              <li>Text objects enable surgical editing operations</li>
              <li>Macros automate repetitive editing tasks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Editing speed once mastered is unmatched</li>
                <li>Available everywhere, especially remote servers</li>
                <li>Terminal-based workflow keeps hands on keyboard</li>
                <li>Extremely lightweight and fast</li>
                <li>Powerful text manipulation capabilities</li>
                <li>Highly customizable and scriptable</li>
                <li>Strong community and extensive plugins</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Steep learning curve requires dedicated practice</li>
                <li>Initial productivity drop can be frustrating</li>
                <li>Configuration requires significant time investment</li>
                <li>Debugging support is limited compared to IDEs</li>
                <li>Terminal-only interface not for everyone</li>
                <li>Plugin compatibility can be fragile</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__setup">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Getting Started with Vim/Neovim</h4>
            <ol class="ess-tool__setup-list">
              <li>Run <code>vimtutor</code> in terminal for interactive 30-minute tutorial covering basics</li>
              <li>Force yourself to use only Vim for one week to build muscle memory</li>
              <li>Install plugin manager (vim-plug for Vim, packer.nvim for Neovim)</li>
              <li>Add essential plugins: fzf for file navigation, LSP for code intelligence, treesitter for syntax</li>
              <li>Configure incrementally, adding features as you discover needs</li>
              <li>Join community forums or Discord servers for configuration help</li>
              <li>Consider pre-configured distributions like LunarVim or AstroNvim for head start</li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Emacs</strong>
                <p>Another powerful, extensible editor with different philosophy. Lisp-based, infinitely customizable. Steep learning curve.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== JetBrains IDEs ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="jetbrains">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="2" y="3" width="20" height="14" rx="2" ry="2"></rect><line x1="8" y1="21" x2="16" y2="21"></line><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12" y2="21"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">JetBrains IDEs</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Professional-grade language-specific IDEs</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$149-$249/year</span>
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free for Students</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>JetBrains produces language-specific IDEs: IntelliJ IDEA for Java/Kotlin, PyCharm for Python, WebStorm for JavaScript, PhpStorm for PHP, and others. Each IDE deeply understands its target language. Code analysis goes beyond syntax checking to detect logic errors, suggest optimizations, and enforce best practices.</p>
          <p>Refactoring tools are the industry standard. Rename a variable, method, or class and the IDE updates every reference across your codebase, including strings and comments where appropriate. Extract method, inline variable, change signature — these operations are safe and comprehensive. For large Java or Python projects, this capability alone justifies the cost.</p>
          <p>Subscription pricing ($149–$249 annually depending on product) includes all updates and a perpetual fallback license. Students and open source projects get free licenses. The resource usage is heavier than lightweight editors but reasonable for modern hardware.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>Advanced refactoring tools that safely transform code across entire projects</li>
              <li>Deep code analysis detects bugs, code smells, and suggests improvements</li>
              <li>Intelligent code completion understands context and types</li>
              <li>Built-in database tools with SQL editing and schema navigation</li>
              <li>Sophisticated debugger with frame navigation and expression evaluation</li>
              <li>Version control integration with local history and merge tools</li>
              <li>Code generation for boilerplate reduction</li>
              <li>Framework-specific support for Spring, Django, React, and others</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Best-in-class refactoring capabilities</li>
                <li>Deep language understanding catches subtle bugs</li>
                <li>Everything integrated and polished</li>
                <li>Excellent for large codebases</li>
                <li>Consistent experience across different language IDEs</li>
                <li>Free for students and open source</li>
                <li>Perpetual fallback license after subscription</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Expensive for individual developers</li>
                <li>Higher resource usage than lightweight editors</li>
                <li>Slower startup time</li>
                <li>Indexing can slow down initial project load</li>
                <li>Subscription model ongoing cost</li>
                <li>May feel heavy for quick edits</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>IntelliJ IDEA Community</strong>
                <p>Free version with Java, Kotlin, Groovy, and Scala support. Missing some enterprise features but fully functional.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Eclipse</strong>
                <p>Free Java IDE with large plugin ecosystem. More dated interface but still capable for Java development.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Emacs ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="emacs">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle><path d="M8 12h8"></path><path d="M12 8v8"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Emacs</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">The extensible, customizable computing environment</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Emacs is less an editor and more a Lisp-based platform for text manipulation. People joke about it being an operating system that happens to include a text editor. The joke has truth: Emacs users read email, browse the web, manage tasks, and edit code without leaving Emacs. Everything is extensible through Emacs Lisp.</p>
          <p>The power comes from extensibility. Don't like how something works? Change it. Need a feature that doesn't exist? Implement it. Thousands of packages provide functionality from Git integration (Magit is considered the best Git interface ever created) to org-mode for task management and literate programming.</p>
          <p>The learning curve rivals Vim's. Keybindings are unique and extensive. Configuration happens in Emacs Lisp, requiring programming knowledge. Distributions like Spacemacs and Doom Emacs provide curated configurations that reduce initial complexity. Once configured to your workflow, Emacs becomes deeply personal and efficient.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Infinitely extensible via Lisp</li>
                <li>Magit is the best Git interface available</li>
                <li>Org-mode unmatched for notes and task management</li>
                <li>Can do everything in one environment</li>
                <li>Decades of packages and community knowledge</li>
                <li>Completely free and open source</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Extremely steep learning curve</li>
                <li>Configuration requires Lisp knowledge</li>
                <li>Default experience is dated</li>
                <li>Keybinding conflicts with modern OS shortcuts</li>
                <li>Can become time sink optimizing configuration</li>
                <li>Package compatibility issues common</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== SECTION 02: TERMINALS & SHELLS ========== -->
  <section id="terminals-shells" class="ess-section" aria-label="Terminals and shells">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">02</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Terminals & Shells</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">The terminal is where developers spend significant time. Modern terminal applications have evolved beyond simple text interfaces to support tabs, splits, themes, and extensive customization. The shell interprets your commands and can be enhanced with plugins for better auto-completion, history search, and visual feedback.</p>

      <!-- ===== iTerm2 ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="iterm2">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="2" y="4" width="20" height="16" rx="2"></rect><line x1="2" y1="8" x2="22" y2="8"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">iTerm2</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">macOS terminal replacement done right</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>iTerm2 replaces macOS Terminal with a feature-rich alternative. Split panes let you view multiple sessions without window juggling. Search works across scrollback with regex support. Hotkey windows show and hide the terminal with a keystroke, keeping it accessible without cluttering your workspace.</p>
          <p>Shell integration provides semantic history, knowing where commands start and end. Click on filenames to open them. Mouse reporting works with programs like vim and tmux. The triggers system can perform actions based on output patterns, like highlighting errors or sending notifications.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Split panes and tabs for multi-tasking</li>
                <li>Powerful search and selection</li>
                <li>Hotkey windows for quick access</li>
                <li>Extensive customization options</li>
                <li>Shell integration features</li>
                <li>Free and actively maintained</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>macOS only</li>
                <li>Can feel overwhelming with features</li>
                <li>Performance impact with many panes</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Windows Terminal ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="windows-terminal">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><polyline points="4 17 10 11 4 5"></polyline><line x1="12" y1="19" x2="20" y2="19"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Windows Terminal</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Microsoft's modern terminal for Windows</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Windows Terminal modernizes the Windows command-line experience. Multiple tabs can host PowerShell, Command Prompt, WSL distributions, or SSH sessions. GPU-accelerated rendering handles large outputs smoothly. The configuration is JSON-based, making customization straightforward and shareable.</p>
          <p>WSL integration is seamless. Launch Ubuntu or any installed distribution in a tab alongside Windows shells. The terminal supports modern features like Unicode and emoji rendering. Custom themes and color schemes make the terminal visually pleasant.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Modern Windows terminal experience</li>
                <li>Excellent WSL integration</li>
                <li>GPU acceleration for performance</li>
                <li>Highly customizable</li>
                <li>Multiple profiles for different shells</li>
                <li>Free and built by Microsoft</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Windows only</li>
                <li>Requires Windows 10 or later</li>
                <li>JSON configuration has learning curve</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Hyper ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="hyper">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 3a3 3 0 0 0-3 3v12a3 3 0 0 0 3 3 3 3 0 0 0 3-3 3 3 0 0 0-3-3H6a3 3 0 0 0-3 3 3 3 0 0 0 3 3 3 3 0 0 0 3-3V6a3 3 0 0 0-3-3 3 3 0 0 0-3 3 3 3 0 0 0 3 3h12a3 3 0 0 0 3-3 3 3 0 0 0-3-3z"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Hyper</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Beautiful, extensible terminal built on web tech</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Hyper takes a different approach, building the terminal in HTML/CSS/JavaScript using Electron. This enables extreme customization through themes and plugins. The extension ecosystem includes everything from Spotify integration to notification systems. Appearance can be styled with CSS.</p>
          <p>The web-based approach has trade-offs. Performance isn't as snappy as native terminals. Resource usage is higher. But for users who value aesthetics and extensibility over raw speed, Hyper delivers a beautiful experience.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Beautiful default appearance</li>
                <li>Highly customizable with CSS</li>
                <li>Plugin ecosystem for extensions</li>
                <li>Cross-platform consistency</li>
                <li>Free and open source</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Slower than native terminals</li>
                <li>Higher resource usage (Electron)</li>
                <li>Can feel sluggish with heavy output</li>
                <li>Development less active recently</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Oh My Zsh / PowerShell ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="oh-my-zsh">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"></path><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5"></path><path d="M2 12l10 5 10-5"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Oh My Zsh / PowerShell</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Shell enhancement frameworks</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Oh My Zsh enhances the Zsh shell with plugins, themes, and better defaults. Auto-completion becomes smarter, suggesting commands based on history and context. Git integration shows branch and status in your prompt. Hundreds of plugins add functionality for specific tools and workflows.</p>
          <p>PowerShell (cross-platform version) provides object-oriented pipelines where commands pass structured data rather than text. Cmdlets follow consistent naming conventions. Scripting capabilities exceed traditional Unix shells. On Windows, it's the preferred automation environment.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Oh My Zsh: Extensive plugin ecosystem</li>
                <li>Better auto-completion out of box</li>
                <li>PowerShell: Object pipelines more powerful</li>
                <li>Both free and cross-platform</li>
                <li>Active communities and support</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Oh My Zsh can slow shell startup</li>
                <li>PowerShell verbosity takes adjustment</li>
                <li>Learning curve for advanced features</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== SECTION 03: DEVELOPER BROWSERS ========== -->
  <section id="developer-browsers" class="ess-section" aria-label="Developer browsers">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">03</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Developer Browsers</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Web developers need browsers with powerful developer tools. Chrome DevTools set the standard that others follow. Network analysis, performance profiling, JavaScript debugging, and responsive design testing all happen in the browser's developer tools.</p>

      <!-- ===== Chrome DevTools ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="chrome-devtools">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="4"></circle><line x1="21.17" y1="8" x2="12" y2="8"></line><line x1="3.95" y1="6.06" x2="8.54" y2="14"></line><line x1="10.88" y1="21.94" x2="15.46" y2="14"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Chrome DevTools</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Industry-standard web development toolkit</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Chrome DevTools is the most comprehensive browser development environment. The Elements panel shows live DOM with computed styles. Network panel reveals every request with timing breakdowns. Performance profiler identifies bottlenecks with flame charts showing exactly where time is spent.</p>
          <p>JavaScript debugging is sophisticated with breakpoints, watch expressions, and call stack navigation. The Console provides REPL access to page JavaScript. Application panel inspects storage, service workers, and PWA manifests. Lighthouse runs audits for performance, accessibility, SEO, and best practices.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Most comprehensive developer tools</li>
                <li>Excellent performance profiling</li>
                <li>Network waterfall analysis</li>
                <li>Lighthouse audits built-in</li>
                <li>Chrome's V8 engine performance</li>
                <li>Largest extension ecosystem</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>High memory usage</li>
                <li>Google tracking concerns</li>
                <li>Battery drain on laptops</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Firefox Developer Edition ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="firefox-dev">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle><path d="M12 2a7 7 0 0 1 7 7c0 3-2 5-4 6"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Firefox Developer Edition</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Privacy-focused browser with excellent dev tools</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Firefox Developer Edition provides Chrome-competitive dev tools with better privacy. CSS Grid and Flexbox inspectors visually show layout structure. Accessibility inspector checks ARIA attributes and contrast ratios. The JavaScript debugger includes time travel debugging through replay.io integration.</p>
          <p>Firefox's rendering engine differs from Chrome's Blink, making it essential for cross-browser testing. The browser blocks tracking by default, protecting your privacy during development. Multi-account containers isolate cookies and storage, useful for testing multiple user scenarios.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Excellent CSS layout tools</li>
                <li>Strong privacy protections</li>
                <li>Different rendering engine aids testing</li>
                <li>Lower memory usage than Chrome</li>
                <li>Multi-account containers</li>
                <li>Open source</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Smaller market share than Chrome</li>
                <li>Some dev tools lag Chrome features</li>
                <li>Extension ecosystem smaller</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Safari Technology Preview ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="safari-preview">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"></circle><polygon points="16.24 7.76 14.12 14.12 7.76 16.24 9.88 9.88 16.24 7.76"></polygon></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Safari Technology Preview</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Apple's experimental browser for web developers</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Safari Technology Preview previews upcoming Safari features before general release. For developers targeting iOS, it's essential for testing. The Web Inspector provides debugging tools matching Chrome and Firefox capabilities. Responsive design mode simulates various iOS devices.</p>
          <p>Safari's WebKit engine powers all iOS browsers, making Safari testing critical for mobile web. The browser's energy efficiency is unmatched on macOS, important for battery-powered testing. Privacy features block tracking aggressively, sometimes breaking sites that assume tracking works.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Essential for iOS testing</li>
                <li>Excellent energy efficiency</li>
                <li>Strong privacy protections</li>
                <li>Native macOS integration</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>macOS only</li>
                <li>Dev tools less polished than Chrome</li>
                <li>Extension ecosystem limited</li>
                <li>Can be behind web standards</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== SECTION 04: DESIGN TOOLS ========== -->
  <section id="design-tools" class="ess-section" aria-label="Design tools">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">04</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Design Tools</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Modern development requires collaboration with designers and sometimes creating designs yourself. Contemporary design tools enable real-time collaboration, developer handoff with code generation, and prototyping that feels interactive.</p>

      <!-- ===== Figma ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="figma">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M5 5.5A3.5 3.5 0 0 1 8.5 2H12v7H8.5A3.5 3.5 0 0 1 5 5.5z"></path><path d="M12 2h3.5a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 0 7H12V2z"></path><path d="M12 12.5a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 7 0 3.5 3.5 0 1 1-7 0z"></path><path d="M5 19.5A3.5 3.5 0 0 1 8.5 16H12v3.5a3.5 3.5 0 1 1-7 0z"></path><path d="M5 12.5A3.5 3.5 0 0 1 8.5 9H12v7H8.5A3.5 3.5 0 0 1 5 12.5z"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Figma</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Collaborative design tool that runs in browsers</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free Tier</span>
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$12-45/editor/mo</span>
          <span class="tag">Web Browser</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows App</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS App</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Figma revolutionized design tools by being browser-based and multiplayer by default. Multiple people can edit the same file simultaneously, seeing each other's cursors move in real time. For developer-designer collaboration, this eliminates the email-attachments workflow entirely.</p>
          <p>The developer handoff experience is excellent. Inspect mode shows CSS, iOS, and Android code for any element. Assets can be exported at multiple resolutions. Design tokens can be extracted to JSON or other formats. Figma doesn't replace communication but makes implementation questions answerable without interrupting designers.</p>
          <p>Component systems with variants mirror frontend component thinking. Auto-layout behaves like Flexbox, making responsive designs easier to create and understand. Plugins extend functionality, often created by the community to solve specific workflow needs.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>Real-time collaborative editing with multiplayer cursors</li>
              <li>Developer handoff with code generation for CSS, iOS, Android</li>
              <li>Component system with variants for design consistency</li>
              <li>Auto-layout mirrors Flexbox for responsive design</li>
              <li>Plugin ecosystem extends functionality</li>
              <li>Version history with branching</li>
              <li>Prototyping with interactive transitions</li>
              <li>Design systems with shared component libraries</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Excellent collaboration features</li>
                <li>Browser-based works everywhere</li>
                <li>Developer handoff built-in</li>
                <li>Free tier generous for small teams</li>
                <li>Fast and responsive</li>
                <li>Active plugin ecosystem</li>
                <li>Constantly improving</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Requires internet connection</li>
                <li>Paid plans get expensive for teams</li>
                <li>Less powerful than Sketch for some workflows</li>
                <li>Now owned by Adobe (acquisition concerns)</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Sketch</strong>
                <p>macOS only, mature tool with extensive plugin ecosystem. One-time purchase plus updates. Strong for UI design.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Adobe XD</strong>
                <p>Adobe's competitor to Figma. Good integration with Adobe ecosystem. Free tier available.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== GIMP ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="gimp">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="3" y="3" width="18" height="18" rx="2" ry="2"></rect><circle cx="8.5" cy="8.5" r="1.5"></circle><polyline points="21 15 16 10 5 21"></polyline></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">GIMP</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Free and open source image editor</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>GIMP provides Photoshop-level image editing without the subscription cost. Layer-based editing, selection tools, filters, and color correction cover most image manipulation needs. For developers who occasionally need to edit images or create graphics, GIMP delivers professional capabilities free.</p>
          <p>The interface follows traditional image editor conventions. Learning curve exists but extensive tutorials are available. Script-Fu and Python-Fu allow automation. File format support is comprehensive, including PSD import for designer handoffs.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Completely free and open source</li>
                <li>Powerful image editing capabilities</li>
                <li>Cross-platform availability</li>
                <li>Extensive plugin support</li>
                <li>No subscription required</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Interface less polished than commercial tools</li>
                <li>Steeper learning curve</li>
                <li>Performance can lag with large files</li>
                <li>Missing some Photoshop features</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Inkscape ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="inkscape">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M12 19l7-7 3 3-7 7-3-3z"></path><path d="M18 13l-1.5-7.5L2 2l3.5 14.5L13 18l5-5z"></path><path d="M2 2l7.586 7.586"></path><circle cx="11" cy="11" r="2"></circle></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Inkscape</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Professional vector graphics editor</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Inkscape handles vector graphics creation and editing. SVG is the native format, making it ideal for web graphics that scale without quality loss. Path operations, text to path conversion, and precise object manipulation support icon and logo creation.</p>
          <p>For developers creating icons, diagrams, or illustrations, Inkscape provides professional tools without Adobe Illustrator's cost. The pen tool takes practice but enables precise curve creation. Export to PNG at any resolution maintains quality.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Free alternative to Illustrator</li>
                <li>Native SVG format</li>
                <li>Powerful vector editing tools</li>
                <li>Cross-platform</li>
                <li>Active development</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Interface can feel dated</li>
                <li>Learning curve for vector graphics</li>
                <li>Performance issues with complex documents</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== SECTION 05: COMMUNICATION ========== -->
  <section id="communication" class="ess-section" aria-label="Communication tools">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">05</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Communication Tools</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Remote work and distributed teams make communication tools essential infrastructure. These platforms enable asynchronous discussion, real-time collaboration, and knowledge sharing across time zones.</p>

      <!-- ===== Slack ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="slack">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M14.5 10c-.83 0-1.5-.67-1.5-1.5v-5c0-.83.67-1.5 1.5-1.5s1.5.67 1.5 1.5v5c0 .83-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5z"></path><path d="M20.5 10H19V8.5c0-.83.67-1.5 1.5-1.5s1.5.67 1.5 1.5-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5z"></path><path d="M9.5 14c.83 0 1.5.67 1.5 1.5v5c0 .83-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5S8 21.33 8 20.5v-5c0-.83.67-1.5 1.5-1.5z"></path><path d="M3.5 14H5v1.5c0 .83-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5S2 16.33 2 15.5 2.67 14 3.5 14z"></path><path d="M14 14.5c0-.83.67-1.5 1.5-1.5h5c.83 0 1.5.67 1.5 1.5s-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5h-5c-.83 0-1.5-.67-1.5-1.5z"></path><path d="M14 20.5c0-.83.67-1.5 1.5-1.5s1.5.67 1.5 1.5-.67 1.5-1.5 1.5-1.5-.67-1.5-1.5z"></path><path d="M10 9.5C10 10.33 9.33 11 8.5 11h-5C2.67 11 2 10.33 2 9.5S2.67 8 3.5 8h5c.83 0 1.5.67 1.5 1.5z"></path><path d="M10 3.5C10 4.33 9.33 5 8.5 5S7 4.33 7 3.5 7.67 2 8.5 2s1.5.67 1.5 1.5z"></path></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Slack</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Team communication organized by channels</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free Tier</span>
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$7.25-12.50/user/mo</span>
          <span class="tag">Web</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
          <span class="tag">iOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Android</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Slack organizes team communication into channels, reducing email clutter. Channels can be public for transparency or private for sensitive discussions. Threading keeps conversations organized without fragmenting them across separate chats. Search across all message history turns Slack into institutional memory.</p>
          <p>Integrations connect Slack to development workflows. GitHub notifications appear in relevant channels. CI/CD systems report build status. Error monitoring services alert teams to production issues. Custom slash commands trigger automated workflows. The app directory provides thousands of pre-built integrations.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Excellent channel organization</li>
                <li>Powerful search and archiving</li>
                <li>Extensive integration ecosystem</li>
                <li>Threading keeps discussions organized</li>
                <li>Works across all platforms</li>
                <li>Free tier suitable for small teams</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Can become noisy and distracting</li>
                <li>Expensive for larger teams</li>
                <li>Free tier limits message history</li>
                <li>Resource heavy on desktop</li>
                <li>Notification management challenging</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Discord</strong>
                <p>Originally for gaming, now popular with dev communities. Better voice/video, free tier more generous. Less business-focused.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Microsoft Teams</strong>
                <p>Integrated with Office 365. Better for organizations already in Microsoft ecosystem. Video conferencing included.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ========== SECTION 06: PRODUCTIVITY APPS ========== -->
  <section id="productivity-apps" class="ess-section" aria-label="Productivity apps">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">06</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Productivity & Note-Taking</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Developers juggle requirements, technical notes, learning resources, and task management. The right productivity tools help organize information, track work, and maintain focus.</p>

      <!-- ===== Notion ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="notion">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M4 4h16c1.1 0 2 .9 2 2v12c0 1.1-.9 2-2 2H4c-1.1 0-2-.9-2-2V6c0-1.1.9-2 2-2z"></path><line x1="8" y1="2" x2="8" y2="22"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Notion</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">All-in-one workspace for notes, docs, and databases</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free Personal</span>
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$8-15/user/mo</span>
          <span class="tag">Web</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">iOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Android</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Notion combines note-taking, task management, databases, and wikis into one flexible system. Pages can contain any combination of text, tables, kanban boards, calendars, and embedded content. The block-based editor makes structuring information intuitive.</p>
          <p>For developers, Notion works well for documentation, technical design docs, learning notes, and personal knowledge bases. Code blocks support syntax highlighting. Database views let you track tasks, bugs, or learning resources with filtering and sorting. Templates accelerate creating consistent page structures.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Extremely flexible and customizable</li>
                <li>Beautiful, modern interface</li>
                <li>Database features unique among note apps</li>
                <li>Real-time collaboration</li>
                <li>Free personal tier generous</li>
                <li>Works across all platforms</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Requires internet connection</li>
                <li>Can be slow with large workspaces</li>
                <li>Learning curve to use effectively</li>
                <li>Offline editing limited</li>
                <li>Export options could be better</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Obsidian</strong>
                <p>Local-first markdown notes with bidirectional linking. Free for personal use. Plugin ecosystem. Better for knowledge graphs.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Trello</strong>
                <p>Kanban-style task management. Simpler than Notion but excellent for visual workflow organization. Free tier available.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>Jira</strong>
                <p>Project management for software teams. Powerful for agile workflows, issue tracking. Overkill for individuals, essential for teams.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
