  <!-- ========== SECTION 10: VIRTUALIZATION ========== -->
  <section id="virtualization" class="ess-section" aria-label="Virtualization software">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="ess-section__header">
        <span class="ess-section__number">10</span>
        <h2 class="ess-section__title">Virtualization Software</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="ess-section__intro">Virtualization enables running multiple operating systems simultaneously on a single machine. Essential for testing cross-platform applications, creating isolated development environments, and running legacy software.</p>

      <!-- ===== VirtualBox ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="virtualbox">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="2" y="3" width="20" height="14" rx="2" ry="2"></rect><line x1="8" y1="21" x2="16" y2="21"></line><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12" y2="21"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Oracle VirtualBox</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Free cross-platform virtualization powerhouse</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag tag-oss">Open Source</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>VirtualBox delivers enterprise-grade virtualization at no cost. It runs any x86 operating system as a guest, making it perfect for testing applications across Windows, Linux distributions, and BSD variants. The snapshot system lets you capture machine states and roll back changes instantly.</p>
          <p>Shared folders bridge the gap between host and guest systems. Network modes range from simple NAT to bridged networking. USB device passthrough, clipboard sharing, and drag-and-drop support reduce friction when working across systems.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__features">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Key Features</h4>
            <ul class="ess-tool__feature-list">
              <li>Snapshot system for instant state capture and rollback during testing</li>
              <li>Shared folders for seamless file transfer between host and guest</li>
              <li>Multiple networking modes including NAT, bridged, and host-only</li>
              <li>USB device passthrough for accessing physical devices in VMs</li>
              <li>Guest Additions for enhanced integration and performance</li>
              <li>Headless mode for running VMs without GUI overhead</li>
              <li>Command-line management via VBoxManage for automation</li>
              <li>Support for all major x86 operating systems as guests</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Completely free with no feature limitations</li>
                <li>Cross-platform host support</li>
                <li>Excellent snapshot and cloning capabilities</li>
                <li>Active development and community support</li>
                <li>Extensive documentation and tutorials</li>
                <li>Easy to use with good GUI</li>
                <li>CLI automation support</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Performance overhead compared to native execution</li>
                <li>Requires significant RAM (4GB+ per VM)</li>
                <li>3D graphics acceleration limited</li>
                <li>CPU virtualization extensions required</li>
                <li>Updates occasionally break existing VMs</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__setup">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Getting Started with VirtualBox</h4>
            <ol class="ess-tool__setup-list">
              <li>Download from <code>virtualbox.org</code> and install for your platform</li>
              <li>Enable CPU virtualization (VT-x/AMD-V) in BIOS if not already enabled</li>
              <li>Download Extension Pack for USB 3.0 and additional features</li>
              <li>Create your first VM: Allocate 2-4GB RAM minimum, 20GB+ storage</li>
              <li>Install Guest Additions in the guest OS for better integration</li>
              <li>Configure shared folders and networking based on your needs</li>
              <li>Take snapshots before major changes or system updates</li>
            </ol>
            <p class="ess-tool__learning-curve"><strong>Learning Curve:</strong> Gentle for basic usage, moderate for advanced networking and automation.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="ess-tool__alternatives">
            <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle">Alternatives to Consider</h4>
            <div class="ess-tool__alt-grid">
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>QEMU</strong>
                <p>Open-source emulator and virtualizer. More powerful but steeper learning curve.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="ess-tool__alt-card">
                <strong>KVM (Linux)</strong>
                <p>Linux kernel-based virtualization with near-native performance. Best for Linux hosts running Linux guests.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== VMware ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="vmware">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="2" y="2" width="20" height="8" rx="2" ry="2"></rect><rect x="2" y="14" width="20" height="8" rx="2" ry="2"></rect><line x1="6" y1="6" x2="6.01" y2="6"></line><line x1="6" y1="18" x2="6.01" y2="18"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">VMware Workstation/Fusion</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Professional virtualization with superior performance</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$199-$299</span>
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free Player Version</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows</span>
          <span class="tag">Linux</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>VMware delivers the most polished virtualization experience available. Virtual machines run noticeably faster thanks to optimized hypervisor technology and better resource management. Advanced networking enables complex virtual network topologies for testing distributed systems.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Best-in-class performance and stability</li>
                <li>Excellent 3D graphics support</li>
                <li>Superior Mac integration (Fusion)</li>
                <li>Advanced networking capabilities</li>
                <li>Free Player for personal use</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Expensive for Pro versions ($199-299)</li>
                <li>Player version lacks advanced features</li>
                <li>Larger resource footprint</li>
                <li>Licensing can be confusing</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Parallels ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="parallels">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="8" y1="3" x2="8" y2="21"></line><line x1="16" y1="3" x2="16" y2="21"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Parallels Desktop</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">macOS virtualization perfected</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-paid">$99/year</span>
          <span class="tag">Subscription</span>
          <span class="tag">macOS</span>
          <span class="tag">Apple Silicon</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Parallels Desktop represents the gold standard for running Windows on Mac. Optimized specifically for macOS, it delivers performance and integration that cross-platform solutions can't match. Coherence mode hides the Windows desktop entirely, presenting Windows apps as native Mac applications.</p>
          <p>Apple Silicon support (M1/M2/M3) runs ARM-based Windows and Linux distributions with remarkable efficiency. Performance on Apple Silicon rivals or exceeds native Windows on similar Intel hardware.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Best Windows-on-Mac performance</li>
                <li>Seamless macOS integration</li>
                <li>Excellent Apple Silicon optimization</li>
                <li>Simple setup with guided installation</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>macOS only</li>
                <li>Subscription pricing ($99/year)</li>
                <li>Requires purchasing Windows license separately</li>
                <li>ARM Windows limitations on Apple Silicon</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>

      <!-- ===== Hyper-V ===== -->
      <article class="ess-tool" id="hyper-v">
        <div class="ess-tool__header">
          <div class="ess-tool__icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="40" height="40" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><rect x="2" y="2" width="20" height="20" rx="2.18" ry="2.18"></rect><line x1="7" y1="2" x2="7" y2="22"></line><line x1="17" y1="2" x2="17" y2="22"></line><line x1="2" y1="12" x2="22" y2="12"></line></svg>
          </div>
          <div class="ess-tool__title-wrap">
            <h3 class="ess-tool__name">Microsoft Hyper-V</h3>
            <p class="ess-tool__tagline">Windows built-in enterprise virtualization</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__tags">
          <span class="tag tag-free">Free</span>
          <span class="tag">Built-in Windows Pro</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows 10/11 Pro</span>
          <span class="tag">Windows Server</span>
        </div>
        <div class="ess-tool__body">
          <p>Hyper-V is Microsoft's Type-1 hypervisor built into Windows Pro and Enterprise editions. Unlike VirtualBox and VMware which run as applications, Hyper-V operates at the kernel level, providing better performance and security isolation. It powers Azure cloud infrastructure and brings enterprise-grade virtualization to developer workstations.</p>

          <div class="ess-tool__pros-cons">
            <div class="ess-tool__pros">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--pros">Pros</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Free with Windows Pro and Enterprise</li>
                <li>Excellent Windows guest performance</li>
                <li>Enterprise-grade security</li>
                <li>PowerShell automation</li>
                <li>Integration with WSL 2 and Docker</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="ess-tool__cons">
              <h4 class="ess-tool__subtitle ess-tool__subtitle--cons">Cons</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Windows Pro/Enterprise only</li>
                <li>Conflicts with VirtualBox and VMware</li>
                <li>Limited USB device passthrough</li>
                <li>Steeper learning curve</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
